tip.text: It's always a good sign when a venue has a really small menu. Yard Sale Pizza not only only do pizza but also have a small menu. Grab one of these scrummy pizzas to eat in or takeaway. We love the butternut squash, goats cheese, rocket and honey drizzle (no mozzarella). For the real meat lovers the pepperoni, fennel sausage, spicy beef, black olives, mixed peppers and mushrooms never goes amiss. It's not all dough though with a selection of salads and some banging beers.

This taqueria has all the spice of a real roadside joint without any of the bowel anxiety. Work your way through a veggie jackfruit taco, topped with crunchy sweet potato; or a taco packed with slow-cooked lamb topped with coriander and onions; and a steak quesadilla perhaps? It's important you know it wouldn't be weird to order one of every taco. No shame; be free, young warrior.

The drinks are just as cray as the colourful decor. Get off on lime, watermelon or cucumber margaritas (with your choice of tequila or mezcal) or try your hand at a 'Michelada', which is basically a beer-based Bloody Mary. Curious aren't you pussy cat?

Ps: It's £2 tacos on Tuesdays. Hells yeah.

Have All Saints started doing cocktail bars? The Bonneville definitely has that vibe, with the shabby walls, ram skulls on the wall, and old school lighting. That curved stained glass ceiling up the back is freakin' gorgeous though, and we have to admit, the whole shabby Parisian feel of the place is a winner...particularly the fog they produce with dry ice.

Old school cocktails are on the menu too, like Mint Juleps, and the menu keeps things French with dishes like Ratatouille. The grub's not bad, but it's the feel of the joint that we love.

The Miyazaki influence is strong here: from the ornate, faded wallpaper to the small toy train perpetually travelling on its lonely loop around the cosy little restaurant, My Neighbours The Dumplings is dripping with the same melancholic charm that the Japanese auteur is known for - you half expect Totoro to show up and whisk you away on a fantastical adventure.

But, alas, the only adventure you’ll be going on at MNTD is of the culinary kind. With a menu committed to the dumpling, paying no mind to geographical differences, you can expect all kinds of innovative pan-Asian dishes that are either 1) dumplings, or 2) designed to compliment dumplings (sometimes we think this is what we were designed for). Made fresh everyday, the parcels themselves are delicate and bursting with flavour, with flairs of innovation wherever you look, while punchy side salads and a sake-focused drinks list offer excellent palate cleansers/time fillers between portions.

It's like Britain and Japan got into a fight, made up, then opened up a cafe together. Pacific Social Club describes itself as a drop-out centre and wannabe Izakaya. What does that mean for you? Great coffee and cakes to the soundtrack of vintage vinyls by day, but in the evenings from Thursday to Saturday you have the mighty Japanese Sho Foo Doh kitchen takeover.

We don't know how they came up with this intercontinental mix, but we wish there were more like it.

This Japanese joint on a Clapton back street is simplicity personified (restaurantified?). Take a seat at the sunken sharing tables (shoes off, of course) or a stool by the window and flick through the short menu. It's sushi, sashimi and nigiri on one section; skewers and hot delicacies on another; and a page at the back for nibbles and puddings. The limited options and simple descriptions give you time to really think about what you'd like to feast on - although our answer is usually 'everything'.

The softshell crab sushi is a real winner; as is the tuna sashimi which comes as three thick slabs of succulent pink fish. As for the hots, we'd tip the grilled mackerel skewers with a tangy sweet vinegar - one of the nicest mouthfuls of fish we'd had in a while. Everything feels straight forward and well considered, and sipping a crisp Japanese lager between each course is a truly pleasurable experience.

We always have a soft spot for ramen, and the stuff at Tonkotsu is consistently bang on. They make their noodles fresh in-house, and the broths they bubble up are rich and mucho meatio. Obviously get stuck in and slurpin on the ramen, but also make sure to sort a side of Chicken Karaage - it's a deep fried wonder.

Also, there's a killer Japanese beer and whisky list to wet your whistles with.

Finally, a Turkish in Hackney that looks a bit different. When we say 'different', we mean it looks like anything but a Turkish. Exposed brick, untreated wood everywhere, but luckily still a menu of kebabs and other charcoal-grilled goodness. Everything you order here comes in a wrap, keeping the mess down.

Thing is, you can get something a bit out the ordinary here. How about some whitebait instead of lamb, and some beers from London breweries?

listing.name: St John at Hackney Brewery x Ela
listing.subtitle: Beautiful Beer & Cypriot Kebabs

tip.text:
A brewery and food joint in a renovated railway arch might not have you rubbing your eyes in shock, but there's plenty more to this place than meets those eyes. Ostensibly, it's a brewery and taproom with a rotating kitchen out back, but the attention to detail here is quite a sight - from the way they make their beer in vats that would have Walter White raising his eyebrows, to the understated beauty of their huge window facade and the 200-year-old church pews that line the walls.

The result is a damn fine place to have a high quality beer (they have 11 lagers, ales and stouts on tap) and get full. It's also deeply rooted in the community, with heavy involvement in local projects in collab with the church of the same name.

Out back is a kitchen currently inhabited by Ela, creators of simple, incredibly tasty Cypriot food. Inspired by the 'world's best kebab shop' in Cyprus, their 'babs come in wondrously marinated chicken, pork or halloumi variations stuffed full of slaws, feta, currents and salads. Big enough to share, these are truly tasty bites. Add in a nice sun-trap garden and hefty speakers and you've got a suitable spot to kick back and let some nice times roll.

It may seem like everyone and their grandma is transforming an abandoned East End railway arch into something or other, but you can't fault Night Tales for their ambition. Set in two arches and an accompanying outdoor area that encompass almost 6,000 square feet, this is a huge Hackney hangout spot offering plenty. There's an Asahi beer garden, covered and heated seating areas, live music from a 300-capacity club space, a large cocktail bar, a beer shack, an in-house Japanese Izakaya restaurant (Fat Baby) and pizza (Sons of Slice).

They've battened down the hatches for winter, covering their huge covered terrace and adding some fire pits, candles and, fear not, dependable heaters pumping out warmth. Just don't think too much about that energy bill. Liable to get lively on weekend evenings, head here for a little hibernation, Hackney style.

When the moon hits your eye like a big pizza pie, thaaaat's amooore... and when you squeeze into a little no-frills pizzeria and eat some of the good stuff straight from a wood-fired oven that's amore too. Poetto in Hackney offers just that, simple honest pizza goodness, priced most favourably and topped with all the love in the world.

Toppings range from mortadella, burrata, and pistachio to parma ham and parmesan, so yeah it's all the classics done to a T. There's also a few salads and a couple of shellfish-heavy pasta dishes on the menu: nothing too wild just good old-fashioned holiday-feeling food. Add craft beer and Italian wine, and you'll have a frightfully good time.

When you heard the chaps behind the Sebright Arms were opening up a restaurant you were excited, right? So were we. And our instincts were right because The Vincent is a very decent all-day brunch & cocktail spot perfect for doing a bit of indulging, offering a bit of a rarity in these parts: substantial bang for your buck.

In a calming wooden oasis featuring big teak lanterns and banana trees, this is a perfect hangover or lazy weekend affair. The menu spans from the healthy to the downright decadent, with classic breakfast offerings joined by stuff like veggie hash, fried chicken and waffle, and their famous bunsmith buns filled with fried chicken or cheeseburgers. But whatever you do, save some space for their waffle with berries and cream - we got it thinking we only wanted a bite, and before we knew it our plate was licked clean.

Strolling up towards this restaurant you’ll pretty likely go ‘oooooooo’ as you see Silver Lining standing proud next to its sister bar Every Cloud. We see what ya did there, veeery clever. Silver Lining is the new venture of Alistair Maddox, aka, the guy who ran Broadway Market for a decade, so it's to be expected that the food is going to be up to it.

The concept is small seasonal plates, and the vibe is light & airy. Kick back and tuck into dishes such as their bavette steak with Padron red pepper sauce, or their jerk chicken scotch eggs with mango and papaya hot sauce. To wash it all down, they've got their famous tipple from Every Cloud on hand. Cocktail big dogs such as their Every Cloud Rusty Nail and Every Cloud Negroni are making the rounds, and should not be missed under *any* circumstance.

Nope, the grimy, iconic Dalston namesake is not setting up a restaurant off-shoot. This cosy little nook - quite like a nest in fact - is the baby of three pals who had been searching for a place to call their home after conquering the pop-up and festival food scene. And they've done a terrific job of it, with a short menu offering beautifully crafted small dishes, either a la carte or on a set menu, that compliment the warm interiors and grooving soundtrack. It's an excellent date-night spot.

The solo chef chooses one meat to work with at a time and bases his dishes around it - we were lucky enough to find duck in the kitchen, and while we're not quite sure how he created the duck steamed pudding, we're awful glad he did. That, and with the crispy garlic potato cake and the celeriac and truffle tart, would be our highlights. With the three owners drifting about the place, this feels very much like a passion project. It's the kind of place to enjoy when you're not in a hurry, when you can sit back over a couple of hours, taking each meticulous dish as it comes.

Isreali-inspired Bernstein’s Bar is a slice of Tel-Aviv cool sitting on a corner of Chatsworth Road. This is an ideal place to take a seat (inside or on the pavement) and watch the Clapton cool cats pass whilst tucking into hearty Middle Eastern dishes; having a coffee; doing the lazy lunch dance; or dipping the beak in something strong and letting the evening take over.

Sourcing plenty of their bits locally, the cuisine here is the comforting chow of Israel and the Levant: fish, meat and cheese sharing boards alongside filling and tasty soups - the chicken stew is known to cure almost every illness known to man. Serving all sorts for all sorts, it’s another vibey spot to add to Clapton’s growing arsenal.

Sometimes you just need carbs and a live Italian band singing to you while you eat.

This casual Italian eatery offers stand-out pizza and pasta and a range of awesome Campari, Prosecco and espresso cocktails at really reasonable prices. A live band belts out Italian tunes on busy nights, and there are more than 25 different pizzas to choose from. AKA endless reasons to stuff your face.

You might walk past Lardo in London Fields thinking it was just another posh warehouse conversion, but once you spot the glimmering disco ball-like pizza oven hanging from the ceiling, you'll know this is a chiller affair. You'll also know it's Lardo, as there's no signage on the door.

There's a lovely outdoor area if you're there on the one night of the year where it's warm enough to sit outside, or plenty of seating and natural light indoors so you can see that warm, sizzling pizza. They also do pasta and all your classic Italian puds (tiramisu, you know we love you), but we'd recommend starting off the night with a cold Spritz and a charcuterie board. Because, why on earth wouldn't you?

We all need that dependable, cheap Middle Eastern joint 'round the corner: giving you a bit of nutritional support when times are tough and times are tiring. Anatolia Ockabasi is just that spot for all of that, beating off some very mixed competition on Mare Street with a nice selection of grilled meats, mezes and pides. A huge big charcoal grill dominates this place and it's a mesmerising sight to see it in action.

This is a no-frills kind of place and that's really how we like our kebabies. Kebabies? Have we just coined something weird and wonderful? Hmm. Our picks include the lamb kofte, the moussaka or the hot mixed meze but really, it's all pretty good. A sensible option if you fancy something tasty but don't want to spend big.

Rawduck lays on some quality all-day dining with fresh seasonal produce at the centre of their breakfast, lunch and dinner menus. We've been known to head there for breakfasts of home-made granolas, oats, and egg dishes with middle eastern bread; comforting pasta lunches and more luxurious dinners.

The drinks are just as exciting here with a rotating list of natural and biodynamic wines and house kombuchas, drinking vinegars and kefirs. Blimey that's a lot of fermenting. Over the summer grab an outdoor bench to nibble your raspberry upside down cake with Iranian pistachios and orange blossom yoghurt. Happy days.

An unassuming restaurant on a quiet stretch of Mare street, Tre Viet is serving up simple, delicious Vietnamese fare on the cheap.

The mural-adorned walls and bamboo-latticed ceiling, complete with hanging lanterns, are so kitsch they come off cosy and charming - and once a steaming bowl of pho is placed in front of you, with the fragrant scents of lemongrass, coriander, and garlic wafting up your nose hole, you’ll be transported straight to the Mekong delta. We'd also recommend any of their sizzling stir frys, just don’t be afraid to go in the with the lime, chilli, and sauces on the table - flavour it up, baby.
